00:02:32.310 --> 00:02:33.610
I'm thinking for today's panel,

00:02:33.610 --> 00:02:34.910
we'd like to roughly
divide the discussion

00:02:34.910 --> 00:02:39.620
into the first half focusing on
the need for some sort of renewals,

00:02:39.620 --> 00:02:42.240
whether this is a presumption
of renewal,

00:02:42.240 --> 00:02:45.160
a burden shifting towards
someone opposing a renewal,

00:02:45.160 --> 00:02:48.310 position:56%
a general streamlining of a
process, whether it's administrative

00:02:48.310 --> 00:02:53.420 position:56%
or statutory reform and then getting
into specific models if possible.

00:02:53.420 --> 00:02:56.470
I realized for this topic,
I think it might be a case

00:02:56.470 --> 00:02:58.390
where the devil's in the details.

00:02:58.390 --> 00:03:01.150
The Register has stated
both in her recommendation

00:03:01.150 --> 00:03:04.340
to the last rulemaking and
in her testimony to Congress

00:03:04.340 --> 00:03:07.370
that the public record
supports amending Section 1201

00:03:07.370 --> 00:03:09.830
to make it easier to
renew exemptions.

00:03:09.830 --> 00:03:13.130 position:56%
She recommended congressional action
to provide a presumption in favor

00:03:13.130 --> 00:03:16.450
of renewal in cases where
there's no meaningful opposition.

00:03:16.450 --> 00:03:19.130
And in the comments that the
Copyright Office has received,

00:03:19.130 --> 00:03:22.830
there seems to be, you know-- I
hate to jinx myself by saying it--

00:03:22.830 --> 00:03:26.170
but some consensus that doing
something would be permissible

00:03:26.170 --> 00:03:29.160
and advisable to deal with
repeated exemption requests.

00:03:29.160 --> 00:03:31.950
But the comment is definitely
diverse in terms of what

00:03:31.950 --> 00:03:33.960
that would look like and
how the concerns are going.

00:03:33.960 --> 00:03:38.120
So, again, I'd like to open up
with a pretty broad question

00:03:38.120 --> 00:03:42.570
of what would your proposal would
be or what are your concerns

00:03:42.570 --> 00:03:47.070
with doing something to make it
easier to facilitate the renewal

00:03:47.070 --> 00:03:50.770
of repeated requests
for an exemption.

00:03:50.770 --> 00:03:52.070
Mr. Sheffner?

00:03:52.070 --> 00:03:53.370
&gt;&gt; Ben Sheffner: Yes.

00:03:53.370 --> 00:03:55.830
First of all, I just
want to agree with you.

00:03:55.830 --> 00:03:57.780
I don't think it'll
jinx the panel to say

00:03:57.780 --> 00:04:01.500 position:56%
that there actually is a
remarkable degree of consensus that,

00:04:01.500 --> 00:04:04.260 position:56%
as to previously granted exemptions,

00:04:04.260 --> 00:04:07.320
there should be some sort
of streamlined process.

00:04:07.320 --> 00:04:13.470
The-- There's too much of a-- it's
really a waste of time and effort

00:04:13.470 --> 00:04:16.000
and burden on both the proponents

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:19.160
and the Copyright Office
staff itself to have to go

00:04:19.160 --> 00:04:24.570
through a full process when there's
really no meaningful opposition.

00:04:24.570 --> 00:04:28.740
So, again, broad consensus
that something should be done.

00:04:28.740 --> 00:04:30.730
And even within the details,

00:04:30.730 --> 00:04:34.710
I don't think there are
dramatic differences.

00:04:34.710 --> 00:04:37.210
As Bruce and I were talking
over the lunch break,

00:04:37.210 --> 00:04:40.110
we were wondering exactly
how even a group

00:04:40.110 --> 00:04:42.710
of opinionated lawyers are
going to be able to fill

00:04:42.710 --> 00:04:46.570
up a full hour-and-a-half
on this particular topic.

00:04:46.570 --> 00:04:51.250
But just a couple of points as
to how we think this should work

00:04:51.250 --> 00:04:57.550
and sort of why we think that our
particular proposal makes sense.

00:04:57.550 --> 00:05:01.050
As we see it, the way it
would work is that proponents

00:05:01.050 --> 00:05:05.890
of a previously granted exemption
who seek renewal should file some--

00:05:05.890 --> 00:05:07.190
make some very simple filing.

00:05:07.190 --> 00:05:13.140
We're talking a page or so stating
that they would like the exemption

00:05:13.140 --> 00:05:15.080
to be renewed and essentially

00:05:15.080 --> 00:05:18.390
to show why they think
it should be renewed.

00:05:18.390 --> 00:05:22.140
Again, we're talking about a very
simple one or two-page filing.

00:05:22.140 --> 00:05:25.730 position:56%
Then, there's a period of time where
if an opponent wants to come forward

00:05:25.730 --> 00:05:28.540
and say, well, actually
we do wish to oppose this

00:05:28.540 --> 00:05:30.930
and briefly here are the reasons,

00:05:30.930 --> 00:05:36.260 position:56%
we think there's still a substantial
debate about whether this would--

00:05:36.260 --> 00:05:40.860
the exemption should be renewed,
then it would go throw it off back

00:05:40.860 --> 00:05:42.180
into the regular process.

00:05:42.180 --> 00:05:46.000
But again, if nobody came forward
to offer any meaningful opposition,

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:48.200
the Copyright Office,
under the existing statute,

00:05:48.200 --> 00:05:51.190
could then just go
ahead and say, you know,

00:05:51.190 --> 00:05:53.730
get out their renewed
stamp and be done

00:05:53.730 --> 00:05:57.500
with that particular
request for an exemption.

00:05:57.500 --> 00:06:02.210
The one thing I'll say
before ending is we do think

00:06:02.210 --> 00:06:05.180
that this proposal should
be limited to renewal

00:06:05.180 --> 00:06:08.740
of the particular exemption
that has been granted.

00:06:08.740 --> 00:06:12.150
And in practice, that is
actually what's happened.

00:06:12.150 --> 00:06:18.510
It's been the exceptional
case, almost a rarity

00:06:18.510 --> 00:06:22.890
where there have been opponents
to previously granted exemptions.

00:06:22.890 --> 00:06:25.890
I know from our perspective in
particular, this last round,

00:06:25.890 --> 00:06:27.610
there were previously
granted exemptions

00:06:27.610 --> 00:06:28.910
that we had opposed in the past.

00:06:28.910 --> 00:06:30.290
Some of those we've lost on.

00:06:30.290 --> 00:06:33.340
But if people came back
and asked for this renewal

00:06:33.340 --> 00:06:35.100 position:56%
of the previously granted exemption,

00:06:35.100 --> 00:06:36.910
as a matter of fact,
this is no secret.

00:06:36.910 --> 00:06:38.350
You could just look in the filings.

00:06:38.350 --> 00:06:41.350
We did not oppose any
of those exemptions.

00:06:41.350 --> 00:06:45.320
We would not want a proposal,
however, to apply to request

00:06:45.320 --> 00:06:48.020
for expansions of previously
granted exemptions.

00:06:48.020 --> 00:06:50.670
If there are new things that
people are wanting to do,

00:06:50.670 --> 00:06:52.230
we should go through
the regular process.

00:06:52.230 --> 00:06:54.880
And again, the burden should
remain on the proponent

00:06:54.880 --> 00:06:57.290 position:56%
of the exemption to make their case.

00:06:57.290 --> 00:06:58.590
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: OK, thank you.

00:06:58.590 --> 00:06:59.890
Mr. Goldman?

00:06:59.890 --> 00:07:01.190
&gt;&gt; Andrew Goldman: Sure.

00:07:01.190 --> 00:07:08.080
Thanks. So KEI, we believe that
there should be presumptive renewal

00:07:08.080 --> 00:07:10.440
of previously granted exemptions.

00:07:10.440 --> 00:07:14.690
I think what we will
say just in response

00:07:14.690 --> 00:07:18.210
to that is it doesn't make sense
to continue to put the burden

00:07:18.210 --> 00:07:21.400
on the party that's already
received the exemption.

00:07:21.400 --> 00:07:23.290
Once the exemption exists,

00:07:23.290 --> 00:07:26.600
the burden should shift
to the copyright holder.

00:07:26.600 --> 00:07:30.620
And I think in the previous
panel, we heard a lot of examples

00:07:30.620 --> 00:07:34.550
of just the waste of
time, the difficulty

00:07:34.550 --> 00:07:37.950
of understanding the
process for the parties

00:07:37.950 --> 00:07:41.940
that are seeking the exemption
and then to continue to have to go

00:07:41.940 --> 00:07:47.130
through that process just
seems wasteful and confusing,

00:07:47.130 --> 00:07:51.460
especially where you have
exemptions that have been granted

00:07:51.460 --> 00:07:56.980
that have been unopposed, as has
been the case with the exemption

00:07:56.980 --> 00:08:01.240
for literary works distributed
electronically to be accessed

00:08:01.240 --> 00:08:04.100
by persons who are blind, visually
impaired or print-disabled.

00:08:04.100 --> 00:08:09.720
The exemptions, I think,
we've seen over time

00:08:09.720 --> 00:08:13.610
and I think this was referred to
by Krista Cox in the last panel,

00:08:13.610 --> 00:08:18.000
we've seen them get increasingly
more complex and lengthy.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:23.590
In 2010, there was a 100-word
exemption for audiovisual works

00:08:23.590 --> 00:08:27.930
which then went to
752 words in 2013.

00:08:27.930 --> 00:08:30.810
And I don't think that
this process should be--

00:08:30.810 --> 00:08:34.500
and KEI does not think that this
process should be so complicated

00:08:34.500 --> 00:08:36.810
and so burdensome for
people that are trying

00:08:36.810 --> 00:08:39.450
to make non-infringing use.

00:08:39.450 --> 00:08:43.340
And, you know, this is
a complicated segment

00:08:43.340 --> 00:08:45.020
of the law, even if you have a JD.

00:08:45.020 --> 00:08:47.630
And you should not have
to have a JD in order

00:08:47.630 --> 00:08:50.540
to have the exemption
and continue to have it.

00:08:50.540 --> 00:08:51.840
Thanks.

00:08:51.840 --> 00:08:53.140
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Thank you.

00:08:53.140 --> 00:08:55.270
Mr. Band?

00:08:55.270 --> 00:08:56.570
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Band: So I'd have

00:08:56.570 --> 00:09:01.310
to study what Mr. Sheffner's
proposal in greater detail.

00:09:01.310 --> 00:09:04.410
But I think in broad strokes,
there's a lot of, you know,

00:09:04.410 --> 00:09:06.280
I would agree with a
lot of what he said.

00:09:06.280 --> 00:09:09.150
At the highest level, I agree
that there's an awful lot more

00:09:09.150 --> 00:09:11.950
that the Copyright Office
itself can do right now

00:09:11.950 --> 00:09:15.090
without any amendment
of the Copyright Act.

00:09:15.090 --> 00:09:18.980
I think way too much deference
has been placed on one sentence

00:09:18.980 --> 00:09:22.370
in one committee report
that actually was directed

00:09:22.370 --> 00:09:23.960
to a different rulemaking, OK?

00:09:23.960 --> 00:09:25.810
It was a rulemaking that
was going to be conducted

00:09:25.810 --> 00:09:28.940
by NTIA, not this rulemaking.

00:09:28.940 --> 00:09:31.960
And so, there's no need for
you to pay any deference

00:09:31.960 --> 00:09:33.310
at all to that one sentence.

00:09:33.310 --> 00:09:36.020
But even to the extent that
you want to pay some deference

00:09:36.020 --> 00:09:42.020
to the de novo sentence, you know,
it's about a de novo determination,

00:09:42.020 --> 00:09:43.980
which is sort of like
what you guys have to do

00:09:43.980 --> 00:09:47.040
or actually what the Librarian
has to do, not what we have to do.

00:09:47.040 --> 00:09:50.150
I mean, you could easily say,
OK, if you want a renewal,

00:09:50.150 --> 00:09:52.550
you could just have the
whole administrative record

00:09:52.550 --> 00:09:56.860
from the previous rulemaking just
incorporated by reference and then,

00:09:56.860 --> 00:10:02.390
you know, then the process
in terms of the, you know,

00:10:02.390 --> 00:10:06.730
what the Register's
recommendation and the NTIA advice

00:10:06.730 --> 00:10:10.620
and the Librarian-- I mean, that
may be have to be somewhat de novo,

00:10:10.620 --> 00:10:12.060
whatever that really means.

00:10:12.060 --> 00:10:14.600
But again, I don't even
think you need to pay

00:10:14.600 --> 00:10:19.730
that much deference
to that one sentence.

00:10:19.730 --> 00:10:21.300
But I think, you know,

00:10:21.300 --> 00:10:25.010
so that really could streamline
the process dramatically

00:10:25.010 --> 00:10:29.140
and so I agree with, you know, Mr.
Sheffner's idea that, you know, if,

00:10:29.140 --> 00:10:32.560
you know, we, if we want a
renewal, we can just do, you know,

00:10:32.560 --> 00:10:37.900
maybe not even a page, you know,
maybe a paragraph or a sentence.

00:10:37.900 --> 00:10:40.630
And then if, you know, even if--

00:10:40.630 --> 00:10:44.260
I would disagree that
if there is opposition,

00:10:44.260 --> 00:10:47.150
then it kicks back into
the normal process.

00:10:47.150 --> 00:10:50.170
I think it should be still
somewhat of a truncated process.

00:10:50.170 --> 00:10:51.820
I mean, I think all of the evidence

00:10:51.820 --> 00:10:55.890
that was previously submitted
should be incorporated

00:10:55.890 --> 00:10:58.340
so that no new evidence
needs to be submitted.

00:10:58.340 --> 00:11:03.280
And so-- And then, you know,
if we as a proponent want

00:11:03.280 --> 00:11:06.340
to propose additional
information, we can.

00:11:06.340 --> 00:11:10.790 position:56%
And if the opponents want to propose
additional information, they can.

00:11:10.790 --> 00:11:19.540
But still, the whole record
should be included and considered

00:11:19.540 --> 00:11:23.210
by the Register and the
Librarian going forward.

00:11:23.210 --> 00:11:25.250
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: And I think
just to kind of pick up on that

00:11:25.250 --> 00:11:31.350
and follow up, we'd be interested,
