00:11:31.350 --> 00:11:36.620
if you agree that under current
law, there is some flexibility

00:11:36.620 --> 00:11:41.840
for the Office to, for
example, consider evidence

00:11:41.840 --> 00:11:46.730
from the prior proceeding, is
anyone aware of any other sort

00:11:46.730 --> 00:11:51.270
of administrative processes
that might provide an analog,

00:11:51.270 --> 00:11:55.250
where the evidentiary record

00:11:55.250 --> 00:11:57.830
from a prior proceeding
could be incorporated?

00:11:57.830 --> 00:11:59.730
That would be helpful for us.

00:11:59.730 --> 00:12:04.070
I think Professor Decherney?

00:12:04.070 --> 00:12:06.160
&gt;&gt; Peter Decherney: Answer
that specific question.

00:12:06.160 --> 00:12:07.460
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Well, that's fine.

00:12:07.460 --> 00:12:10.510 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Peter Decherney: I was just going
to say that it's actually very--

00:12:10.510 --> 00:12:11.810
time doesn't stand still.

00:12:11.810 --> 00:12:14.070
Technology doesn't stand still.

00:12:14.070 --> 00:12:15.900
Uses of technology
doesn't stand still.

00:12:15.900 --> 00:12:19.470
So it's very unusual
to have a renewal

00:12:19.470 --> 00:12:21.270
that would look exactly the same

00:12:21.270 --> 00:12:23.250
as the exemption looked
three years ago.

00:12:23.250 --> 00:12:26.290
But I don't think that's a
reason to throw out the proposal.

00:12:26.290 --> 00:12:29.250
There may be another way
of saying we want to start

00:12:29.250 --> 00:12:33.960 position:56%
where we left off last time and then
think about additions or changes.

00:12:33.960 --> 00:12:37.230
I'm not always sure that there
are even additions or expansions.

00:12:37.230 --> 00:12:40.500
So sometimes it's just an
updating of the existing exemption

00:12:40.500 --> 00:12:42.920
so that it accounts for
current states of technology

00:12:42.920 --> 00:12:44.540
and the way that it's used.

00:12:44.540 --> 00:12:47.090
And so, maybe there's just
another way of doing it

00:12:47.090 --> 00:12:50.770
so that we don't have the same
conversation from the beginning.

00:12:50.770 --> 00:12:52.780
We don't start at the
beginning line.

00:12:52.780 --> 00:12:55.730
You know, we start where
we left off last time.

00:12:55.730 --> 00:12:57.030
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Thank you.

00:12:57.030 --> 00:12:59.330
So I think there's two issues,
what Kevin has followed up on

00:12:59.330 --> 00:13:02.000
and also what you've just raised in
terms of expanding the exemption.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:05.950 position:56%
But I wonder if we could stick first
to see if there's some consensus

00:13:05.950 --> 00:13:09.950
around roughly what Mr.
Sheffner proposed in terms

00:13:09.950 --> 00:13:14.320
of a short form filing prior
to the rulemaking proper.

00:13:14.320 --> 00:13:16.510
And I wonder Mr. Cazares,
is that something

00:13:16.510 --> 00:13:19.360
that would work for
your organization?

