of adverse impact will be
in the next three years.

00:26:18.840 --> 00:26:26.410
The other thing is that for any
form of streamlined proceeding

00:26:26.410 --> 00:26:30.990
of previously granted
exemptions, the exemptions

00:26:30.990 --> 00:26:36.400
that are renewed should be
the exact same exemption

00:26:36.400 --> 00:26:38.540
that was approved before.

00:26:38.540 --> 00:26:40.540 position:56%
If there are any changes, of course,

00:26:40.540 --> 00:26:43.300
there can be some form
of middle proceeding.

00:26:43.300 --> 00:26:46.580
And I think it has
been suggested before

00:26:46.580 --> 00:26:50.020
that it's not exactly kicked
back to what we have today,

00:26:50.020 --> 00:26:52.790
but something in between
for additions or changes

00:26:52.790 --> 00:26:55.410
to previously granted exemptions.

00:26:55.410 --> 00:26:58.230
So, I think it's worth it for
the Copyright Office to sort

00:26:58.230 --> 00:27:05.210 position:56%
of contemplate having several tracks
or something along those lines.

00:27:05.210 --> 00:27:10.450
And then the other issue I've
heard is that there seems

00:27:10.450 --> 00:27:14.540
to be some favoring of an
automatic renewal presumption.

00:27:14.540 --> 00:27:18.590
And the problem with that is that
then, that would be very similar

00:27:18.590 --> 00:27:21.740
to having permanent exemptions.

00:27:21.740 --> 00:27:25.180
And that is something
for the panel tomorrow.

00:27:25.180 --> 00:27:30.020 position:56%
But for purposes of renewal, I think
it's important to take into account

00:27:30.020 --> 00:27:33.890
that having this proceeding every
three years is helpful to account

00:27:33.890 --> 00:27:35.770
for changes in the marketplace.

00:27:35.770 --> 00:27:38.930
And if we have an automatic
renewal presumption,

00:27:38.930 --> 00:27:42.250
then that would sort
of take that away.

00:27:42.250 --> 00:27:44.530
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Thank you.

00:27:44.530 --> 00:27:48.450
Mr. Geiger?

00:27:48.450 --> 00:27:53.340
&gt;&gt; Harley Geiger: So, we hire
a lot of security researchers

00:27:53.340 --> 00:27:56.700
and white hat hackers and we
also work with a large number

00:27:56.700 --> 00:28:00.360
of independent security
researchers that we do not employ.

00:28:00.360 --> 00:28:05.250
And most of these researchers are
working either solo or as part

00:28:05.250 --> 00:28:07.110
of some sort of very small shop.

00:28:07.110 --> 00:28:09.930
And most of them, the vast majority

00:28:09.930 --> 00:28:13.300 position:56%
of them do not possess the requisite
legal expertise to even deal

00:28:13.300 --> 00:28:17.160 position:56%
with cease-and-desist letters
telling them to stop their research,

00:28:17.160 --> 00:28:20.840
often making vague claims about
DMCA, let alone for engaging

00:28:20.840 --> 00:28:22.810
in the temporary renewal process.

00:28:22.810 --> 00:28:25.630
So from our perspective, we
absolutely support a presumption

00:28:25.630 --> 00:28:30.490
of renewal and it sounds like
these are the fault lines,

00:28:30.490 --> 00:28:33.120
based on what the rest of
the panel has been saying,

00:28:33.120 --> 00:28:35.410
and obviously where
we come down on it.

00:28:35.410 --> 00:28:39.350
When it comes to the burden
of the initial filing,

00:28:39.350 --> 00:28:42.040
Mr. Sheffner had suggested
that it should be the proponent

00:28:42.040 --> 00:28:44.180
of the exemption that
makes that initial filing.

00:28:44.180 --> 00:28:47.370
We would support an
automatic renewal.

00:28:47.370 --> 00:28:51.310
And the idea that it would just
be one page I'm not sure is going

00:28:51.310 --> 00:28:52.680
to hold for very long.

00:28:52.680 --> 00:28:55.650
This is one reason why I
think that the opponents ought

00:28:55.650 --> 00:28:57.830 position:56%
to be the ones that make the filing.

00:28:57.830 --> 00:29:00.020
That one page could
very well expand,

00:29:00.020 --> 00:29:02.590
unless it's restricted
to a single page.

00:29:02.590 --> 00:29:04.860
And then, every word on that
page is going to get litigated

00:29:04.860 --> 00:29:07.360
and you will once again need
legal expertise in order

00:29:07.360 --> 00:29:11.610 position:56%
to make a good filing, one that does
not trip you up later down the line.

00:29:11.610 --> 00:29:16.070
When it comes to the-- losing
that presumption of renewal,

00:29:16.070 --> 00:29:18.890
we've talked about whether there
should be meaningful opposition

00:29:18.890 --> 00:29:20.960
that cancels the presumption
of renewal.

00:29:20.960 --> 00:29:23.650
And I don't think that
that's the right standard

00:29:23.650 --> 00:29:28.500 position:56%
because if anybody objects, which is
Mr. Sheffner's original proposition,

00:29:28.500 --> 00:29:31.560
if anybody objects and we shunt
into the original process again,

00:29:31.560 --> 00:29:34.010
but as we have seen in
previous rulemakings,

00:29:34.010 --> 00:29:37.790
the same arguments are trotted
out over and over again.

00:29:37.790 --> 00:29:39.970
There's no reason why those same
arguments would simply not be

00:29:39.970 --> 00:29:43.230
trotted out again and then cancel
the presumption and shunt you back

00:29:43.230 --> 00:29:44.530
into the original process.

00:29:44.530 --> 00:29:46.440
And then, what really is
the presumption worth,

00:29:46.440 --> 00:29:49.720
except for something that
is completely unopposed.

00:29:49.720 --> 00:29:53.450
When it comes to-- So instead,
instead of meaningful opposition,

00:29:53.450 --> 00:29:55.320
I think that a better
standard would be whether

00:29:55.320 --> 00:29:58.480
or not there has been some sort of
material change in circumstances.

00:29:58.480 --> 00:30:00.090
We've talked about
changes in the marketplace,

00:30:00.090 --> 00:30:02.040
changes in technology and so forth.

00:30:02.040 --> 00:30:05.740 position:56%
Those types of changes are different
than simply meaningful opposition.

00:30:05.740 --> 00:30:07.680
I think that that would
be a better standard.

00:30:07.680 --> 00:30:08.980
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: So the-- oh, sorry.

00:30:08.980 --> 00:30:10.280
Go ahead.

00:30:10.280 --> 00:30:11.580
&gt;&gt; Harvey Geiger: Go ahead.

00:30:11.580 --> 00:30:13.390
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: So the presumption
would kick in automatically

00:30:13.390 --> 00:30:18.080
and then just the burden
automatically would be on opponents

00:30:18.080 --> 00:30:21.180
to establish a material
change in circumstances?

00:30:21.180 --> 00:30:22.480 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Harvey Geiger: Yes, that's right.

00:30:22.480 --> 00:30:26.690
And I'll take it a step further,
which is to say that-- two things.

00:30:26.690 --> 00:30:28.820
One, if we're talking about
an expansion, you know,

00:30:28.820 --> 00:30:32.150
above and beyond the
original exemption,

00:30:32.150 --> 00:30:36.090
we think that the process ought
to then be about that expansion,

00:30:36.090 --> 00:30:38.690
as opposed to the expansion
plus the original.

00:30:38.690 --> 00:30:41.320
And lastly, and this goes
to the evidentiary standard

00:30:41.320 --> 00:30:44.550
for the exemption, not just
a renewal, we don't think

00:30:44.550 --> 00:30:49.070 position:56%
that non-copyright interests that go
beyond protecting copyrighted works

00:30:49.070 --> 00:30:51.840
or protecting the availability of
copyrighted works ought to figure

00:30:51.840 --> 00:30:56.450
in to the denial of the
exemption, including a rebutting

00:30:56.450 --> 00:30:59.450
of the presumption that you
would get the exemption again.

00:30:59.450 --> 00:31:03.140
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: So, I think that
leads right into another question.

00:31:03.140 --> 00:31:07.380
As you indicated, the proposal that
Mr. Sheffner outlined, I think,

00:31:07.380 --> 00:31:11.040
as I understand it, is
premised on lack of opposition,

00:31:11.040 --> 00:31:16.450
lack of meaningful opposition
or some variant of that.

00:31:16.450 --> 00:31:20.370
Do we have another
alternative which would be--

00:31:20.370 --> 00:31:23.130
which would provide that
the presumption would kick

00:31:23.130 --> 00:31:24.590
in automatically.

00:31:24.590 --> 00:31:28.970
I wonder if panelists have
views about, you know,

00:31:28.970 --> 00:31:31.230
which model is preferable?

00:31:31.230 --> 00:31:33.890
And if the standard is
meaningful opposition,

00:31:33.890 --> 00:31:35.790
what would that mean exactly?

00:31:35.790 --> 00:31:39.740
Would the Copyright Office have
some discretion to sort of--

00:31:39.740 --> 00:31:45.730
to make a determination as to
how meaningful an opposition is?

00:31:45.730 --> 00:31:48.990
We'd be grateful for
your thoughts about it.

00:31:48.990 --> 00:31:50.290
Mr. Sheffner?

00:31:50.290 --> 00:31:51.590
&gt;&gt; Ben Sheffner: Thank you.

00:31:51.590 --> 00:31:55.250
So, we do oppose the idea
of a presumption of renewal

00:31:55.250 --> 00:31:56.660
of previously granted exemptions.

00:31:56.660 --> 00:31:59.300
And Ms. Castillo touched
on some of the reasons.

00:31:59.300 --> 00:32:04.290
But I want to expand a little bit.

00:32:04.290 --> 00:32:07.940
First thing I'd say is don't
necessarily listen to my reasoning.

00:32:07.940 --> 00:32:09.240
But I would just point you back

00:32:09.240 --> 00:32:11.570
to the Copyright Office's
own reasoning back

00:32:11.570 --> 00:32:15.150
in the rule issued on
October 27th, 2000.

00:32:15.150 --> 00:32:18.040
And I won't repeat what the
Copyright Office wrote here.

00:32:18.040 --> 00:32:22.360
But in sum, the Copyright Office
looked at general principles

00:32:22.360 --> 00:32:25.890
of statutory construction
and administrative law.

00:32:25.890 --> 00:32:31.140
And again, summarizing, essentially
what the Copyright Office concluded

00:32:31.140 --> 00:32:34.550
from looking at the legal
authority is that essentially

00:32:34.550 --> 00:32:37.610
when you have a statute and then
you have exemptions to that statute

00:32:37.610 --> 00:32:40.090 position:56%
or exceptions to the statute, again,

00:32:40.090 --> 00:32:41.800
those rules of statutory
construction

00:32:41.800 --> 00:32:45.620
and administrative
law say that, one,

00:32:45.620 --> 00:32:48.260
the exemption should be
construed narrowly and, two,

00:32:48.260 --> 00:32:52.430
that the burden should be on the
proponent of those exemptions.

00:32:52.430 --> 00:32:55.610
So, again, the Copyright
Office concluded this based

00:32:55.610 --> 00:32:57.710
on sound legal reasoning
back in 2000.

00:32:57.710 --> 00:33:00.960 position:56%
And I don't think there has been
any change in the general principles

00:33:00.960 --> 00:33:02.260
of statutory construction

00:33:02.260 --> 00:33:05.320
or administrative law
that have changed.

00:33:05.320 --> 00:33:08.680
That said, I want to emphasize

00:33:08.680 --> 00:33:15.160
that the discussion we're having is
largely academic for two reasons.

00:33:15.160 --> 00:33:19.180
One is, as I stated previously,
there, at least in the last round,

00:33:19.180 --> 00:33:21.780
and I think this is sort
of becoming the practice,

00:33:21.780 --> 00:33:25.890
there is virtually no opposition
to previously granted exemptions.

00:33:25.890 --> 00:33:28.030 position:56%
Just as a matter of fact, even those

00:33:28.030 --> 00:33:34.720
who previously opposed an exemption
are sort of looking at the state

00:33:34.720 --> 00:33:36.910
of affairs once it's been
granted and saying, you know what,

00:33:36.910 --> 00:33:40.920 position:56%
for whatever reason, whether we
can't come up with a showing of harm

00:33:40.920 --> 00:33:43.070
or just a sort of political
recognition

00:33:43.070 --> 00:33:45.340
that the Copyright
Office is not likely

00:33:45.340 --> 00:33:48.600
to reverse a determination
they've made in the past,

00:33:48.600 --> 00:33:51.780
we're simply not opposing that.

00:33:51.780 --> 00:33:53.970
And the other thing I
want to emphasize is

00:33:53.970 --> 00:33:58.510
that although the burden should
remain on the proponents, it's--

00:33:58.510 --> 00:34:00.410
we're only talking about
a presumption here.

00:34:00.410 --> 00:34:04.100
So if you had no presumption, you'd
assume both sides start at 50/50.

00:34:04.100 --> 00:34:09.500 position:56%
If there is a presumption-- if
there is a presumption of nonrenewal

00:34:09.500 --> 00:34:12.420
or not a presumption in favor
of renewal, the proponents start

00:34:12.420 --> 00:34:15.920
at 49 and the opponents at 51.

00:34:15.920 --> 00:34:20.810 position:56%
But again, as long as they make some
sort of minimal evidentiary showing

00:34:20.810 --> 00:34:24.040
that they are entitled to that
exemption under the statute,

00:34:24.040 --> 00:34:27.340
they will overcome that
presumption and therefore,

00:34:27.340 --> 00:34:30.230
the Copyright Office
would be entitled to get

00:34:30.230 --> 00:34:32.790
out of their rubber
stamp of renewal.

00:34:32.790 --> 00:34:36.760
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Mr. Turnbull?

00:34:36.760 --> 00:34:38.060 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Bruce Turnbull: I think I'd agree

00:34:38.060 --> 00:34:39.680
with pretty much everything
that was just said.

00:34:39.680 --> 00:34:47.250 position:56%
But let me just add that, I mean,
truly it seems to me that the burden

00:34:47.250 --> 00:34:53.060
on making the initial statement,
yes, we want to renew, I mean,

00:34:53.060 --> 00:34:56.460
could be-- I mean, it could
be a checkbox on a form.

00:34:56.460 --> 00:35:03.130
And if the Copyright Office emails
that form to the prior proponent

00:35:03.130 --> 00:35:07.150
and says, do you want to renew
exactly what you got before,

00:35:07.150 --> 00:35:10.060
and you check the box, I
mean, as far as I'm concerned,

00:35:10.060 --> 00:35:12.510
that would be a sufficient filing.

00:35:12.510 --> 00:35:16.840
I really did not mean this
to be any kind of a burden.

00:35:16.840 --> 00:35:22.540
I mean, that's the-- but it seems
to me that under the statute,

00:35:22.540 --> 00:35:24.690
you do need to go through
the process

00:35:24.690 --> 00:35:27.580
of actually getting a request.

00:35:27.580 --> 00:35:29.920
You can use, as we said before,

00:35:29.920 --> 00:35:35.180
the prior evidentiary record
as the basis for that.

00:35:35.180 --> 00:35:37.840
That satisfies the
requirement that this be done

00:35:37.840 --> 00:35:41.830
in a rulemaking, it seems to me.

00:35:41.830 --> 00:35:47.470
And the opposition-- I'm sort
of trying to come up with--

00:35:47.470 --> 00:35:51.520
I understand the point about making
the same argument all over again.

00:35:51.520 --> 00:35:56.390
I-- That does seem to be a
waste of everybody's time,

00:35:56.390 --> 00:36:02.570
except maybe for the lawyer
who bills by the hour.

00:36:02.570 --> 00:36:07.200
But the-- So, there is some
kind of changed circumstances,

00:36:07.200 --> 00:36:11.590
changed argument, there was a
change in the law that something

00:36:11.590 --> 00:36:15.200
that people thought was fair
use was found not to be fair use

00:36:15.200 --> 00:36:21.010
or there was an abuse
of the prior exemption

00:36:21.010 --> 00:36:26.520
or somebody actually came
forward with a circumvention tool

00:36:26.520 --> 00:36:30.450
that would turned out to be a
huge problem in the marketplace.

00:36:30.450 --> 00:36:35.380
I mean, those are the kinds of
things that I can imagine often

00:36:35.380 --> 00:36:38.130
as an opponent coming
forward and saying, hey,

00:36:38.130 --> 00:36:39.540
you really ought to
look at this again.

00:36:39.540 --> 00:36:43.850
Those are the kinds of
changes that I would see

00:36:43.850 --> 00:36:47.730
as needing to be brought forward.

00:36:47.730 --> 00:36:51.210
That's not a matter of presumptions
or burden shifting in my view.

00:36:51.210 --> 00:36:53.580
It's just a matter of
practical, as has been said,

00:36:53.580 --> 00:36:56.220
as a practical matter, you know,

00:36:56.220 --> 00:37:00.220 position:56%
DVD CCA has not opposed the previous
exemptions that were granted

00:37:00.220 --> 00:37:03.420
and I don't foresee
doing so in the future.

00:37:03.420 --> 00:37:06.930
Again, absent some specific change.

00:37:06.930 --> 00:37:10.840
And there, I think we ought
to be able to come forward

00:37:10.840 --> 00:37:13.940
and say there's been a
change and here it is.

00:37:13.940 --> 00:37:15.240
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Thank you.

00:37:15.240 --> 00:37:16.860
Mr. Band, do you want to speak
following up on this question

00:37:16.860 --> 00:37:21.250
of whether, you know, the ease of
showing whether there's changed

00:37:21.250 --> 00:37:23.720
or unchanged circumstances
as sort of a precondition

00:37:23.720 --> 00:37:25.970
to renewing an exemption?

00:37:25.970 --> 00:37:27.270
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Band: Yes.

00:37:27.270 --> 00:37:34.240
So, it seems to me that to some
extent this whole discussion of,

00:37:34.240 --> 00:37:38.680
you know, presumptions and burden
shifting is not really appropriate

00:37:38.680 --> 00:37:39.980
to a rulemaking.

00:37:39.980 --> 00:37:43.190
I mean, you know, those are terms
that are much more appropriate

00:37:43.190 --> 00:37:44.790
to an adjudicatory proceeding.

00:37:44.790 --> 00:37:49.740 position:56%
And this rulemaking has, for
whatever reason, has over time taken

00:37:49.740 --> 00:37:54.450
on more and more of this
adjudicatory quality to it.

00:37:54.450 --> 00:37:56.740
But it's really not necessary.

00:37:56.740 --> 00:37:59.430
And, you know, it seems
that, you know,

00:37:59.430 --> 00:38:04.750
getting back to your earlier
question about, you know, yes,

00:38:04.750 --> 00:38:07.540
the statute would require
the Librarian

00:38:07.540 --> 00:38:10.720
to make a determination
that, you know, there's--

00:38:10.720 --> 00:38:14.690
harm is occurring or
is likely to occur.

00:38:14.690 --> 00:38:17.880
I mean, to some extent, that
can, in this renewal context,

00:38:17.880 --> 00:38:23.660
can occur if the checked box says
do you want to renew this exemption

00:38:23.660 --> 00:38:28.120
because you are being harmed
or likely to be harmed

00:38:28.120 --> 00:38:30.340
over the next three years.

00:38:30.340 --> 00:38:35.370
And then, that would seem to
me, you know, just on its face,

00:38:35.370 --> 00:38:38.580
that statement plus
the incorporation

00:38:38.580 --> 00:38:43.710
of the administrative record from
the previous would be sufficient

00:38:43.710 --> 00:38:48.320
for the Librarian, on the basis
of sort of making, you know,

00:38:48.320 --> 00:38:52.720 position:56%
looking at-- I mean, I don't-- I
wouldn't-- I'm not sure I would go--

00:38:52.720 --> 00:38:56.640
I think if we just-- the
rubber stamp is probably not--

00:38:56.640 --> 00:39:02.480 position:56%
might not pass APA muster, but that
the Librarian, based on that record,

00:39:02.480 --> 00:39:07.980
would say, well, you know, a good
case was made three years ago.

00:39:07.980 --> 00:39:10.750
There doesn't seem to be
any changed circumstances.

00:39:10.750 --> 00:39:14.970
These people say that they're
likely to be harmed again.

00:39:14.970 --> 00:39:16.810
OK, I will approve it.

00:39:16.810 --> 00:39:19.850
I don't think we need to
start getting into, you know,

00:39:19.850 --> 00:39:22.240
burden shifting, presumption,
all that kind of stuff.

00:39:22.240 --> 00:39:26.750
Now, it is conceivable that someone
will come out of the woodwork

00:39:26.750 --> 00:39:30.250
and say, no, I don't
want this renewed.

00:39:30.250 --> 00:39:31.550
And again, we're talking--

00:39:31.550 --> 00:39:35.630
now, I agree that if we want an
exemption expanded, you know,

00:39:35.630 --> 00:39:38.730
that's on us to talk about
why it should be expanded.

00:39:38.730 --> 00:39:43.720
But if we're just talking about,
you know, the renewal of, you know,

00:39:43.720 --> 00:39:49.070
the renewal of the existing
one, you know, then--

00:39:49.070 --> 00:39:52.430
you know, conceivably if someone
comes in and says, no, you know,

00:39:52.430 --> 00:39:54.740
it shouldn't be renewed,
you know, that's something

00:39:54.740 --> 00:39:59.000
that the Register would look
at in the recommendation

00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:01.680
to see whether they
made a sufficient--

00:40:01.680 --> 00:40:05.910
you know, whether what they
said was sufficiently compelling

00:40:05.910 --> 00:40:07.210
about changes or whatever.

00:40:07.210 --> 00:40:15.100
But in conceivably in, you know,
the notice soliciting comments,

00:40:15.100 --> 00:40:17.650
you would explain the
kinds of things

00:40:17.650 --> 00:40:18.950
that you would be looking for.

00:40:18.950 --> 00:40:20.530
But again, I don't think
we need to start talking

00:40:20.530 --> 00:40:22.870
about evidentiary burdens
or anything of the sort.

00:40:22.870 --> 00:40:26.350
I mean, these would be things that
would be considered in the course

00:40:26.350 --> 00:40:31.850
of this determination, in a
rulemaking context as opposed

00:40:31.850 --> 00:40:34.280
to an adjudicatory context.

00:40:34.280 --> 00:40:36.610
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Well, so I
think with the check the box

00:40:36.610 --> 00:40:38.940
and rubber stamp, we've
lightened the workload

00:40:38.940 --> 00:40:40.240
of the Copyright Office.

00:40:40.240 --> 00:40:41.700
But I think--

00:40:41.700 --> 00:40:43.000
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Band: Which
is our objective.

00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:44.300
That's why we're all here.

00:40:44.300 --> 00:40:45.600
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Well, that's great.

00:40:45.600 --> 00:40:47.050
But from a rulemaking perspective,

00:40:47.050 --> 00:40:51.030
I wonder if we can speak a
little bit more about, you know,

00:40:51.030 --> 00:40:54.340
whether this-- the Office has
previously said that a declaration

00:40:54.340 --> 00:40:57.390
of unchanged circumstances
could be considered

00:40:57.390 --> 00:40:58.690
in renewing any exemption.

00:40:58.690 --> 00:41:02.560
Are there ways we could use that or
build upon that to make the renewal

00:41:02.560 --> 00:41:04.940
of previously granted
exemptions easier?

00:41:04.940 --> 00:41:08.210
So Professor Tushnet?

00:41:08.210 --> 00:41:09.790
&gt;&gt; Rebecca Tushnet: So
you asked earlier on,

00:41:09.790 --> 00:41:11.560
and I think this is
another version of it,

00:41:11.560 --> 00:41:14.550
whether a one-page statement
could meet the statutory burden

00:41:14.550 --> 00:41:16.400
as the Office has interpreted it.

00:41:16.400 --> 00:41:19.730
And I think the answer
is absolutely yes, right?

00:41:19.730 --> 00:41:22.080
If it says nothing has changed.

00:41:22.080 --> 00:41:23.530 position:56%
In other administrative proceedings,

00:41:23.530 --> 00:41:26.450
facts that aren't contested
are routinely accepted,

00:41:26.450 --> 00:41:28.210
even without going
back to the bedrock.

00:41:28.210 --> 00:41:32.450 position:56%
I mean, certainly, if you do want to
look at the PTO as a model, in fact,

00:41:32.450 --> 00:41:35.210
you can rely on things
like a statement

00:41:35.210 --> 00:41:37.480
of five years of uncontested use.

00:41:37.480 --> 00:41:39.600
The PTO can actually rely
on that not just to say

00:41:39.600 --> 00:41:41.800
that there's been five
years of uncontested use,

00:41:41.800 --> 00:41:44.720
but that that has a legal
consequence that the mark

00:41:44.720 --> 00:41:46.630
at issue has developed
a secondary meaning.

00:41:46.630 --> 00:41:52.660 position:56%
So, it's actually perfectly
standard to accept things like that.

00:41:52.660 --> 00:41:55.480
Now, I also would like
to say a little bit

00:41:55.480 --> 00:41:57.720
about the meaningful
opposition question.

00:41:57.720 --> 00:42:00.580
So, this is just specific
to our experience

00:42:00.580 --> 00:42:03.020
with the remix exemptions.

00:42:03.020 --> 00:42:07.770
What we hear in the remix exemption
proceedings is the statement our

00:42:07.770 --> 00:42:10.740
arguments about the facts and
the law apply to both existing

00:42:10.740 --> 00:42:13.240
and proposed exemptions, but
we do not oppose renewal.

00:42:13.240 --> 00:42:15.840
And if you go back and look,
you'll see that structure

00:42:15.840 --> 00:42:18.630
in basically everyone's,
opponent's comments.

00:42:18.630 --> 00:42:20.410
And one question I would have

00:42:20.410 --> 00:42:22.760
for this meaningful opposition
standard is, how are we going

00:42:22.760 --> 00:42:24.550
to interpret a claim like that?

00:42:24.550 --> 00:42:26.510
Does that represent
meaningful opposition

00:42:26.510 --> 00:42:27.810
to the existing exemption?

00:42:27.810 --> 00:42:31.990
Since it's an argument against
it, would we just not take

00:42:31.990 --> 00:42:33.720
in to its logical conclusion?

00:42:33.720 --> 00:42:36.480
And let me just with my
law professor hat on,

00:42:36.480 --> 00:42:41.030
so if the evidence is
relevant to both the existing

00:42:41.030 --> 00:42:45.750
and proposed expansions, then an
adjudicatory model does allow you

00:42:45.750 --> 00:42:49.820
to ignore that fact
because parties are allowed

00:42:49.820 --> 00:42:52.470
to make strategic concessions,
right?

00:42:52.470 --> 00:42:57.440
But a rulemaking model might not.

00:42:57.440 --> 00:42:59.570
And so, one thing at issue here is

00:42:59.570 --> 00:43:02.360
to decide what this
proceeding will be.

00:43:02.360 --> 00:43:04.690
And once we have a
better grasp on that,

00:43:04.690 --> 00:43:06.900
some of the answers will follow.

00:43:06.900 --> 00:43:10.160
But I think right now,
we actually are,

00:43:10.160 --> 00:43:11.860
as Jonathan was saying,
we go back and forth.

00:43:11.860 --> 00:43:13.210
Some is adjudicatory.

00:43:13.210 --> 00:43:14.510
Some is rulemaking.

00:43:14.510 --> 00:43:18.230
You know, and that's part
of what makes it difficult.

00:43:18.230 --> 00:43:21.920
And then relatedly, just again
for the remix specifically,

00:43:21.920 --> 00:43:25.930
in terms of meaningful opposition,
as a practical matter, you know,

00:43:25.930 --> 00:43:29.760
I expect that the opponents will
always come back saying, hey,

00:43:29.760 --> 00:43:31.980
there's a new screen
cap program out,

00:43:31.980 --> 00:43:33.280
you know, there's a new processor.

00:43:33.280 --> 00:43:35.490
It's faster and it's better.

00:43:35.490 --> 00:43:37.200
And, you know--

00:43:37.200 --> 00:43:38.830
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: But
you've heard next to you--

00:43:38.830 --> 00:43:40.130
&gt;&gt; Rebecca Tushnet: Yeah.

00:43:40.130 --> 00:43:41.430 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: -- the general
opponents saying they don't do that.

00:43:41.430 --> 00:43:42.730 position:56%
They don't oppose the existing ones.

00:43:42.730 --> 00:43:44.730
&gt;&gt; Rebecca Tushnet: But if-- I
encourage you then to go back

00:43:44.730 --> 00:43:48.100
and look at the comments
because they're absolutely right.

00:43:48.100 --> 00:43:49.600 position:56%
They're saying they don't oppose it.

00:43:49.600 --> 00:43:52.200
But the arguments they make--
and they say this too--

00:43:52.200 --> 00:43:54.520
the arguments they make
apply to both the existing

00:43:54.520 --> 00:43:57.210
and the proposed extension
but they are not opposing.

00:43:57.210 --> 00:43:58.920
And so, one question for you

00:43:58.920 --> 00:44:05.070
as decision-maker is what
consequences ought that concession,

00:44:05.070 --> 00:44:07.490
if it is a concession, have?

00:44:07.490 --> 00:44:08.790
Right, does that count?

00:44:08.790 --> 00:44:10.370
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Sure, and I
mean, just since our goal is

00:44:10.370 --> 00:44:12.840
to build consensus, I think in
the past, the Office took them

00:44:12.840 --> 00:44:15.930
at their word when they said they
were not opposing and held them

00:44:15.930 --> 00:44:18.520
to that as opposed to saying,
well, some of your arguments

00:44:18.520 --> 00:44:20.620
on the expansions would
apply to the existing.

00:44:20.620 --> 00:44:22.290
&gt;&gt; Rebecca Tushnet: Well, so, and I
understand, and my point is simply

00:44:22.290 --> 00:44:25.690
that that makes sense in
an adjudicative model.

00:44:25.690 --> 00:44:27.430
But if you're really
thinking about this

00:44:27.430 --> 00:44:29.800
as being a rulemaking fact-finder

00:44:29.800 --> 00:44:32.800
with independent fact-finding
obligations,

00:44:32.800 --> 00:44:35.570
then that is an intrusion
into the model.

00:44:35.570 --> 00:44:39.780
And at the very least, we
should talk openly about that.

00:44:39.780 --> 00:44:42.080
And this is somewhat a statement
against one's interests, I admit.

00:44:42.080 --> 00:44:45.840
But, you know, I'd like
to know the answer.

00:44:45.840 --> 00:44:47.140
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Mr. McClure?

00:44:47.140 --> 00:44:49.600
&gt;&gt; Sam McClure: I'd just like to
make one more quick comment maybe

00:44:49.600 --> 00:44:53.630
about the idea of presumptive
renewal, which is that it's--

00:44:53.630 --> 00:44:55.640
an organization is
tied to this exempt--

00:44:55.640 --> 00:44:59.470
if you don't presumptively renew,
then you have one organization,

00:44:59.470 --> 00:45:02.440
the original proponent perhaps,
being tied to this exemption,

00:45:02.440 --> 00:45:03.740
you know, process after process.

00:45:03.740 --> 00:45:07.690
And I think the point was made
by Mr. Butler and Mr. Geiger

00:45:07.690 --> 00:45:10.130
that once the exemption
is granted, it's something

00:45:10.130 --> 00:45:14.310
that benefits the public at large
who falls within that class, right?

00:45:14.310 --> 00:45:17.210
It shouldn't have to be one
organization that comes back

00:45:17.210 --> 00:45:19.760
and year after year, you
know, sort of lives in fear

00:45:19.760 --> 00:45:22.180
that someone is going to
present meaningful opposition

00:45:22.180 --> 00:45:23.570
and they're going to go
back into this, you know,

00:45:23.570 --> 00:45:25.750 position:56%
hundred-hour, thousand-hour process.

00:45:25.750 --> 00:45:30.320
So, to the extent that an exemption
would be presumptively renewed,

00:45:30.320 --> 00:45:33.810
the burden on that particular
organization would be relieved.

00:45:33.810 --> 00:45:35.110
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:45:35.110 --> 00:45:37.080
Mr.-- Professor Decherney?

00:45:37.080 --> 00:45:39.450
&gt;&gt; Peter Decherney: I just
want to expand a little bit

00:45:39.450 --> 00:45:41.650
on Professor Tushnet's point.

00:45:41.650 --> 00:45:45.140
The structure of the comments
I've seen from the DVD CCA,

00:45:45.140 --> 00:45:47.260
the MPAA is always we're--

00:45:47.260 --> 00:45:49.340
in theory, we're not
opposed to the renewal.

00:45:49.340 --> 00:45:52.790
But we think it could be limited
in these 10 ways, 20 ways.

00:45:52.790 --> 00:45:55.720
And we actually spend a tremendous
amount of time refuting each

00:45:55.720 --> 00:45:57.860
of those ways in which
it would be limited.

00:45:57.860 --> 00:46:00.560
And much of the hearing time
is spent discussing those.

00:46:00.560 --> 00:46:03.210
So even though it says
it's not an opposition,

00:46:03.210 --> 00:46:05.620
it is in fact opposition.

00:46:05.620 --> 00:46:07.610
Just one other structural
issue, which I know--

00:46:07.610 --> 00:46:09.820
we mentioned it in comments
but it hasn't come up here

00:46:09.820 --> 00:46:12.020
and I just wanted to
bring it up is, you know,

00:46:12.020 --> 00:46:16.310
if you do a brilliant job
drafting the previous exemption,

00:46:16.310 --> 00:46:19.830
then you've actually eliminated
this problem for three years.

00:46:19.830 --> 00:46:21.360
And so, it's hard to
show that the harm

00:46:21.360 --> 00:46:23.140
that existed three
years prior still exists

00:46:23.140 --> 00:46:26.500
because the problems
have been solved.

00:46:26.500 --> 00:46:28.960
You can show that the exemption
has been taken, made use of

00:46:28.960 --> 00:46:31.730
or caused problems,
led to infringement.

00:46:31.730 --> 00:46:35.790
But you can't show the exact
same harm that was there before.

00:46:35.790 --> 00:46:39.810
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: So you think you
can't show unchanged circumstances

00:46:39.810 --> 00:46:41.110
because you made the--

00:46:41.110 --> 00:46:42.540
&gt;&gt; Peter Decherney: I mean, that's
true in life in general, yes.

00:46:42.540 --> 00:46:44.660
[ Laughter ]

00:46:44.660 --> 00:46:45.960
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Thank you.

00:46:45.960 --> 00:46:47.290
Mr. Turnbull?

00:46:47.290 --> 00:46:51.420
&gt;&gt; Bruce Turnbull: I think the
point's been made about the nature

00:46:51.420 --> 00:46:56.380
of the filing in the
comments and I-- fair points.

00:46:56.380 --> 00:47:01.540
And I think the Office has
appropriately taken those,

00:47:01.540 --> 00:47:03.240
as was indicated.

00:47:03.240 --> 00:47:05.590
I think the procedure
that we're now talking

00:47:05.590 --> 00:47:11.170
about would probably eliminate
that approach to the comments

00:47:11.170 --> 00:47:14.960
because you'd be forced up
front to either say, you know,

00:47:14.960 --> 00:47:18.820
there are meaningful differences
and there are changes or not.

00:47:18.820 --> 00:47:25.230
And so, I think that the
procedure would naturally eliminate

00:47:25.230 --> 00:47:27.370
that sort of problem.

00:47:27.370 --> 00:47:31.190
I think the-- And then, would
force us to say, well, gee,

00:47:31.190 --> 00:47:34.760
is there really a change that we
want to argue here with regard

00:47:34.760 --> 00:47:40.420
to the old exemption or is it
something where we want to say no,

00:47:40.420 --> 00:47:43.590
that we're only going to argue with
regard to whatever the change is.

00:47:43.590 --> 00:47:46.290
And I understand that that--

00:47:46.290 --> 00:47:53.350
And the points that have
been made are fair on that.

00:47:53.350 --> 00:47:54.790
The other thing is,
I mean, throughout--

00:47:54.790 --> 00:47:58.600
sending an email to a previous
applicant with a checkbox,

00:47:58.600 --> 00:48:01.300
I wouldn't rule out
somebody else coming in

00:48:01.300 --> 00:48:03.500
and saying I've been
taking advantage of this

00:48:03.500 --> 00:48:08.660 position:56%
and I want this renewed, even if the
organization that originally filed--

00:48:08.660 --> 00:48:09.960
I didn't mean to preclude that.

00:48:09.960 --> 00:48:13.380
I was just trying to be
helpful in making it easier.

00:48:13.380 --> 00:48:16.750
So, I think, you know,
anybody who can represent

00:48:16.750 --> 00:48:19.400
that they are taking
advantage of the exemption

00:48:19.400 --> 00:48:22.920
and believe it should be renewed as
previously stated ought to be able

00:48:22.920 --> 00:48:24.600
to make that application.

00:48:24.600 --> 00:48:28.700
And then, we would have to decide
whether there's a reason to oppose.

00:48:29.920 --> 00:48:32.730
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Mr. Cazares?

00:48:32.730 --> 00:48:34.980
&gt;&gt; Gabe Cazares: So, from
the perspective of people

00:48:34.980 --> 00:48:37.670
with disabilities, I know
that the National Federation

00:48:37.670 --> 00:48:42.690
of the Blind fully supports
presumptive automatic renewal.

00:48:42.690 --> 00:48:46.940
I think many at this table
remember the 2010 cycle

00:48:46.940 --> 00:48:49.960
when another disability
organization,

00:48:49.960 --> 00:48:52.520
the American Foundation
for the Blind, was very--

00:48:52.520 --> 00:48:56.600
came very close to
losing the exemption

00:48:56.600 --> 00:49:02.430 position:56%
that they had previously renewed
because of evidentiary requirements.

00:49:02.430 --> 00:49:07.560
So I think there's something
to be said for taking

00:49:07.560 --> 00:49:10.030
into account the points that
have already been raised

00:49:10.030 --> 00:49:14.850
by the Copyright staff and other
panelists about the statute

00:49:14.850 --> 00:49:19.860
and the limitation that the
Librarian has to keep in mind.

00:49:19.860 --> 00:49:22.880
I think it's safe to say,
particularly for blind

00:49:22.880 --> 00:49:26.840
and print-disabled individuals,
that within three years,

00:49:26.840 --> 00:49:29.510
our status as blind

00:49:29.510 --> 00:49:33.760
and print-disabled people
really isn't going to change,

00:49:33.760 --> 00:49:40.460
and that it can be argued that
we would be adversely affected

00:49:40.460 --> 00:49:43.340
by not having an exemption.

00:49:43.340 --> 00:49:47.200
So, I think that NFB fully
supports what Mr. Goldman

00:49:47.200 --> 00:49:49.860
and others have already brought up.

00:49:49.860 --> 00:49:55.210
But there is something to be
said about finding some mechanism

00:49:55.210 --> 00:49:59.010
where we can simply say
we're requesting an exemption

00:49:59.010 --> 00:50:00.310
under the given rules.

00:50:00.310 --> 00:50:07.600
Now, not to bring up another point,
I think it's important to consider

00:50:07.600 --> 00:50:09.810
where the burden of
proof is right now.

00:50:09.810 --> 00:50:12.910
I think Mr. Band made a really
good point that this is more

00:50:12.910 --> 00:50:14.580
of an adjudicatory issue.

00:50:14.580 --> 00:50:17.820
But because of-- that's-- because
these are the circumstances

00:50:17.820 --> 00:50:21.430
that we have now, I think
there is something to be said

00:50:21.430 --> 00:50:24.390
from shifting the burden
from the, first,

00:50:24.390 --> 00:50:26.570
from the proponent
to the opposition.

00:50:26.570 --> 00:50:28.490
So, I just wanted to make
sure that that was clear,

00:50:28.490 --> 00:50:30.870
at least for people
with disabilities.

00:50:30.870 --> 00:50:32.190
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:50:32.190 --> 00:50:34.560
Mr. Geiger?

00:50:34.560 --> 00:50:39.390 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Harley Geiger: So, it sounds
like we've heard some more consensus

00:50:39.390 --> 00:50:41.610
than perhaps we had
originally thought

00:50:41.610 --> 00:50:44.860
on what meaningful
opposition ought to look like

00:50:44.860 --> 00:50:48.460 position:56%
and perhaps it should be something
more like a change in circumstances.

00:50:48.460 --> 00:50:52.440
So I want to draw back to an
earlier comment that I've made,

00:50:52.440 --> 00:50:56.530
which I know relates to also to the
panel on the evidentiary standard,

00:50:56.530 --> 00:50:59.150
which is that in thinking
about whether

00:50:59.150 --> 00:51:03.160
to renew a temporary exemption,
it's our position that interests

00:51:03.160 --> 00:51:06.820
that do not have anything to do
with protecting rights-holders

00:51:06.820 --> 00:51:09.900
or making copyrighted works
available, we do not think

00:51:09.900 --> 00:51:13.940
that those should be considered
for denying the exemption.

00:51:13.940 --> 00:51:15.940
In addition-- Or, you
know, or at least have them

00:51:15.940 --> 00:51:20.870
as a very clearly carrying
much lower weight.

00:51:20.870 --> 00:51:23.700
From the perspective of security
researchers, most of the opposition

00:51:23.700 --> 00:51:27.520
that we have seen so far to
the exemption that we had asked

00:51:27.520 --> 00:51:30.130 position:56%
for relates not at all to copyright.

00:51:30.130 --> 00:51:32.140
It is about safety largely.

00:51:32.140 --> 00:51:35.240
So we have, for example, a
vehicle practice and we're looking

00:51:35.240 --> 00:51:37.370
at cybersecurity flaws
in vehicles with the goal

00:51:37.370 --> 00:51:39.300
of making those vehicles safer.

00:51:39.300 --> 00:51:43.820
We saw opponents talking about
the possibility that owners

00:51:43.820 --> 00:51:49.060
of cars would circumvent emissions
controls or modify their vehicles

00:51:49.060 --> 00:51:50.360
in a way that is not safe.

00:51:50.360 --> 00:51:51.660
These things are already illegal.

00:51:51.660 --> 00:51:54.650
In the last panel, it was brought
up, well, what about the hacker

00:51:54.650 --> 00:51:57.130
that says they want to hack
the nuclear power plant.

00:51:57.130 --> 00:51:58.430
That's also illegal.

00:51:58.430 --> 00:52:01.550
That's all illegal under the
Computer Fraud and Abuse Act.

00:52:01.550 --> 00:52:05.020
By in large, the DMCA we're
talking about are computers

00:52:05.020 --> 00:52:07.430
that the security researcher
already owns.

00:52:07.430 --> 00:52:12.120
And copyright law and 1201 are
not the appropriate tool to use

00:52:12.120 --> 00:52:14.090
to protect these non-copyright
interests.

00:52:14.090 --> 00:52:16.480
There are already specific
government agencies

00:52:16.480 --> 00:52:19.310
with greater expertise and in
many cases already regulations

00:52:19.310 --> 00:52:23.000
on the books prohibiting
these very same kinds of acts.

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:24.560
So, that is our position,

00:52:24.560 --> 00:52:29.890 position:56%
not accommodating non-copyright
interests for denying the exemption.

00:52:29.890 --> 00:52:32.380
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: In the specific
case of security researchers,

00:52:32.380 --> 00:52:34.440
1201(j) is a permanent exemption.

00:52:34.440 --> 00:52:35.770
And I know you're going
to speak tomorrow.

00:52:35.770 --> 00:52:40.000
I mean, is that perhaps a better
avenue to just sort of update

00:52:40.000 --> 00:52:41.720
that to the extent it needs updated

00:52:41.720 --> 00:52:46.180
so that security researchers can
rely on it as opposed to, you know,

00:52:46.180 --> 00:52:48.820
tinkering with the whole mechanism
of the rule-making process?

00:52:48.820 --> 00:52:50.340
&gt;&gt; Harley Geiger: One
hundred percent, yes.

00:52:50.340 --> 00:52:52.310
And I mean, I'm in
the same position as--

00:52:52.310 --> 00:52:53.610
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Mr. Butler.

00:52:53.610 --> 00:52:54.910
&gt;&gt; Harley Geiger: --
Mr. Butler that we think

00:52:54.910 --> 00:52:57.680
that this is less preferable than
updating the permanent exemption.

00:52:57.680 --> 00:53:00.290
Part of the problem with, you know,
even a change in circumstances is

00:53:00.290 --> 00:53:01.590
that technology will evolve.

00:53:01.590 --> 00:53:03.070
Security research will also evolve.

