of what meaningful
opposition would look like.

01:19:31.410 --> 01:19:34.460 position:56%
You know, we were not terribly
specific in our own written comments

01:19:34.460 --> 01:19:36.700
about exactly how the
process should work.

01:19:36.700 --> 01:19:38.000
But let me just sort of spell it

01:19:38.000 --> 01:19:41.000
out how I envision in
kind of non-legalese.

01:19:41.000 --> 01:19:43.670
I mean, what I envision
is essentially a sort

01:19:43.670 --> 01:19:48.960 position:56%
of prescreening process that the
Copyright Office would employ before

01:19:48.960 --> 01:19:51.940
delving into sort of the regular
process that we've all gotten used

01:19:51.940 --> 01:19:54.260
to over the last six cycles or so.

01:19:54.260 --> 01:19:57.280
So, the initial step
would be the proponent

01:19:57.280 --> 01:20:00.090
of a previously granted
exemption filing something short.

01:20:00.090 --> 01:20:02.400
We can argue about whether
it's a page or a checkbox

01:20:02.400 --> 01:20:04.430
or a paragraph or whatever.

01:20:04.430 --> 01:20:07.460
And then, the-- essentially what
the Copyright Office is going

01:20:07.460 --> 01:20:09.600
to be asking itself, or
should be asking itself,

01:20:09.600 --> 01:20:11.310
is do we have a real fight here.

01:20:11.310 --> 01:20:16.150
Do we have a real fight between
sort of two sets of arguments

01:20:16.150 --> 01:20:20.270
or do we have essentially an
unopposed request for an exemption?

01:20:20.270 --> 01:20:25.800
So, the opponent of the
previously granted exemption,

01:20:25.800 --> 01:20:28.100
again in this rare case where
someone is actually going

01:20:28.100 --> 01:20:31.020
to come forward and oppose a
previously granted exemption,

01:20:31.020 --> 01:20:33.800
I would just say, again, it's
going to be a one-page form

01:20:33.800 --> 01:20:38.520 position:56%
and they're going to identify why
there is meaningful opposition here.

01:20:38.520 --> 01:20:41.260
Is it because that there's,
you know, a short description,

01:20:41.260 --> 01:20:42.610
there is a change--

01:20:42.610 --> 01:20:44.920
they've discovered that
there's actually great harm

01:20:44.920 --> 01:20:48.480
or significant harm from
the previously granted--

01:20:48.480 --> 01:20:53.180
from the exception to the
prohibitions in the DMCA?

01:20:53.180 --> 01:20:57.130
Is there a changed case law
that would touch on whether

01:20:57.130 --> 01:20:59.550
or not the use at issue
was non-infringing?

01:20:59.550 --> 01:21:04.220
Is there new technology that would
make possible what the proponents

01:21:04.220 --> 01:21:06.680
want to do without
circumventing the DRM?

01:21:06.680 --> 01:21:07.980
That kind of thing.

01:21:07.980 --> 01:21:10.930
Again, a short form that allows
the Copyright Office to look at it

01:21:10.930 --> 01:21:12.970
and say, you know,
do this prescreening

01:21:12.970 --> 01:21:16.490
and say do we have a real
substantial fight on our hand

01:21:16.490 --> 01:21:19.220
or is this essentially a, you know,

01:21:19.220 --> 01:21:23.260
a no-brainer where there's no
significant, no meaningful,

01:21:23.260 --> 01:21:25.940
whatever the right
word is, opposition.

01:21:25.940 --> 01:21:29.190
And if there is, then again,
it just gets shunted back

01:21:29.190 --> 01:21:30.730
into the regular process.

01:21:30.730 --> 01:21:33.390
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: And then,
would you think if the Office

01:21:33.390 --> 01:21:36.660
in its prescreening determined
it was sort of insufficient

01:21:36.660 --> 01:21:39.500
under administrative law principles
or something, we could go back

01:21:39.500 --> 01:21:43.000
and say give us a little more,
like Mr. Band was saying, or--

01:21:43.000 --> 01:21:45.720
&gt;&gt; Ben Sheffner: Yeah, again,
I mean, we haven't specified a,

01:21:45.720 --> 01:21:48.810
you know, a whole set of processes.

01:21:48.810 --> 01:21:52.310
And like Mr. Band, I wouldn't
want to make it too complicated.

01:21:52.310 --> 01:21:54.620
But I mean, I think at a
high level, that's what--

01:21:54.620 --> 01:21:57.470 position:56%
I mean, I just explained what I
think the Copyright Office should be

01:21:57.470 --> 01:22:00.100
trying to do is screen
out, OK, are we--

01:22:00.100 --> 01:22:02.200
do we have a real fight
here or do we not?

01:22:02.200 --> 01:22:05.850
And again, in the vast,
vast majority of cases

01:22:05.850 --> 01:22:08.520
where somebody has gotten
an exemption already,

01:22:08.520 --> 01:22:10.010
there is not going
to be a real fight.

01:22:10.010 --> 01:22:11.980
There's not going to be an
opponent who has shown up.

01:22:11.980 --> 01:22:15.160
And they're not going to bother
to show up unless they really,

01:22:15.160 --> 01:22:17.700
really have a good reason
that I'm sure they'll be able

01:22:17.700 --> 01:22:20.240
to identify in a page or two.

01:22:20.240 --> 01:22:21.690
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: People will
probably hold you to that.

01:22:21.690 --> 01:22:22.990
Just kidding.

01:22:22.990 --> 01:22:24.290
Mr. Turnbull?

01:22:24.290 --> 01:22:31.190
&gt;&gt; Bruce Turnbull: I would agree
with that and only add that I think

01:22:31.190 --> 01:22:34.500
that the nature and quantum
of evidence that would need--

01:22:34.500 --> 01:22:37.800
or argument that would need to
come forward will depend a bit

01:22:37.800 --> 01:22:40.820
on what the previous grant was.

01:22:40.820 --> 01:22:44.330
If the previous grant is
this is really a close case,

01:22:44.330 --> 01:22:48.160
but we think that, you know, it's
OK, you know, and we'll, you know,

01:22:48.160 --> 01:22:52.540
we'll go forward, then you may not
need as much to come back and say,

01:22:52.540 --> 01:22:55.080 position:56%
yeah, there is a real argument here.

01:22:55.080 --> 01:22:57.450
If the previous was, you know,

01:22:57.450 --> 01:23:01.390
if it's already been granted three
times and this is the, you know,

01:23:01.390 --> 01:23:07.940 position:56%
the fourth time around and it's just
clear as a bell but that end up--

01:23:07.940 --> 01:23:12.430
the opinion, the recommendation
is really clear, then it's going

01:23:12.430 --> 01:23:15.550
to take more to come back and
say, no, there's really now--

01:23:15.550 --> 01:23:17.850
there really now is a new argument.

01:23:17.850 --> 01:23:20.430
There really now is new
evidence or whatever.

01:23:20.430 --> 01:23:25.650
I just-- And again, I think that--
I mean, agreeing that it'll take--

01:23:25.650 --> 01:23:27.660
it'll be in your discretion.

01:23:27.660 --> 01:23:34.280
But, you know, I think that
that-- the level is going to be--

01:23:34.280 --> 01:23:38.030
it'll be a pretty apparent
in any given case.

01:23:38.030 --> 01:23:43.210
And your question about if somebody
submits something and you go, well,

01:23:43.210 --> 01:23:45.650
on its face, that really
doesn't do it,

01:23:45.650 --> 01:23:47.970
but we're not quite sure
what you're getting at, yeah,

01:23:47.970 --> 01:23:51.990
I think that you ought to have
the discretion to go back and say,

01:23:51.990 --> 01:23:54.580
you say that there's
new case law or you say

01:23:54.580 --> 01:23:57.710 position:56%
that there's some new technology but
you're really not describing that.

01:23:57.710 --> 01:24:00.210
If we're going to reopen
this, you know,

01:24:00.210 --> 01:24:06.020
into a full evidentiary
hearing, we need more than that.

01:24:06.020 --> 01:24:08.910
And, you know, maybe,
you know, not giving--

01:24:08.910 --> 01:24:12.360
not extending it out a long time
or giving, you know, repetitive.

01:24:12.360 --> 01:24:15.350
But it seems to me that you would
have the discretion to do that.

01:24:15.350 --> 01:24:18.590
I would hope that the lawyers
representing the opponents would

01:24:18.590 --> 01:24:23.140
come forward and do well
in the first instance.

01:24:23.140 --> 01:24:25.800
But if there was a
question, I think that it's

01:24:25.800 --> 01:24:28.190
within your discretion
to ask for more.

01:24:28.190 --> 01:24:29.490
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Thank you.

01:24:29.490 --> 01:24:30.880
Professor Tushnet?

01:24:30.880 --> 01:24:32.930
&gt;&gt; Rebecca Tushnet: So just
briefly, I wanted to talk

01:24:32.930 --> 01:24:36.500
about the characteristic or the
characterization of checking a box

01:24:36.500 --> 01:24:39.000
as like somehow not
meeting your burden.

01:24:39.000 --> 01:24:42.210
I mean, I don't think that's
just checking a box any more

01:24:42.210 --> 01:24:45.360
than when you check a box
saying you've submitted truthful

01:24:45.360 --> 01:24:48.660 position:56%
information on your tax return, that
that's a meaningless or trivial act.

01:24:48.660 --> 01:24:52.160
It's an affirmation that the
conditions at issue continue

01:24:52.160 --> 01:24:54.560
to exist, or exist in the
case of the tax return.

01:24:54.560 --> 01:24:59.640
So, it seems to me that in order
to refute the box, the checked box,

01:24:59.640 --> 01:25:01.700
you should have to show those
conditions and laws have changed,

01:25:01.700 --> 01:25:03.440 position:56%
just like the IRS would want to show

01:25:03.440 --> 01:25:05.070
that in fact that wasn't
your income.

01:25:05.070 --> 01:25:08.460
And, you know, and if you want me
to, I will submit the entire record

01:25:08.460 --> 01:25:10.480
from the last three
rulemakings as attachments

01:25:10.480 --> 01:25:12.160
so you can consider them submitted.

01:25:12.160 --> 01:25:13.490
But that seems kind of trivial.

01:25:13.490 --> 01:25:15.670
I mean, I would be happier if
you considered the checkmark

01:25:15.670 --> 01:25:17.580
to be me making that submission.

01:25:17.580 --> 01:25:22.260
If we all agreed that that was what
I was doing, then it seems to me

01:25:22.260 --> 01:25:25.520 position:56%
that we then have a full submission.

01:25:25.520 --> 01:25:29.910
It's just, you know, one
that's already in your books.

01:25:29.910 --> 01:25:31.210
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Thank you.

01:25:31.210 --> 01:25:32.510
Mr. Geiger?

01:25:32.510 --> 01:25:37.150
&gt;&gt; Harley Geiger: So in this
renewal process that we're talking

01:25:37.150 --> 01:25:41.480
about here, we've talked about
having a one-page of why we,

01:25:41.480 --> 01:25:45.400
you know, of meaningful opposition
of why circumstances have changed.

01:25:45.400 --> 01:25:48.210 position:56%
And if the Copyright Office then, in
its discretion, decides that it is

01:25:48.210 --> 01:25:50.900
in fact meaningful, then they kick
it over to the normal process.

01:25:50.900 --> 01:25:54.760
I would-- You know, unfortunately,
it would be a more complex process.

01:25:54.760 --> 01:25:58.900
But I would suggest that in
between those two actions,

01:25:58.900 --> 01:26:02.530
you actually give the proponent
the opportunity to respond,

01:26:02.530 --> 01:26:05.340
the proponent the opportunity
to say, no,

01:26:05.340 --> 01:26:08.530
the meaningful opposition is not
meaningful and here's why because,

01:26:08.530 --> 01:26:10.680 position:56%
you know, otherwise-- and hopefully,

01:26:10.680 --> 01:26:13.280
that will inform the
Copyright Office

01:26:13.280 --> 01:26:16.610
to better exercise its discretion
before beginning the long

01:26:16.610 --> 01:26:18.450
and laborious process of going

01:26:18.450 --> 01:26:21.660
through the whole temporary
exemption again.

01:26:21.660 --> 01:26:22.960
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Thank you.

01:26:22.960 --> 01:26:26.330
Mr. Butler, I think you
may have the last word.

01:26:26.330 --> 01:26:27.630
&gt;&gt; Brandon Butler: Yeah.

01:26:27.630 --> 01:26:31.290
So, it's getting complicated
now, isn't it?

01:26:31.290 --> 01:26:34.840
The one-pagers are proliferating,
which is good for those

01:26:34.840 --> 01:26:36.270
of us who bill by the hour.

01:26:36.270 --> 01:26:41.910
But I don't anymore, so-- and I
wonder-- ultimately, I think, my--

01:26:41.910 --> 01:26:44.100
I guess this may be
too obvious to say.

01:26:44.100 --> 01:26:47.550
But ultimately, the folks who
oppose I think are going to have

01:26:47.550 --> 01:26:51.110
to come forward with
some real information

01:26:51.110 --> 01:26:53.590
to explain why they think
circumstances have changed.

01:26:53.590 --> 01:26:57.040
And so, I don't know-- I
just wonder how useful it is,

01:26:57.040 --> 01:27:01.220
unless the Office is willing, I
think, to say based on a one-pager

01:27:01.220 --> 01:27:04.560
and the opponents are willing to
be judged based on a one-pager,

01:27:04.560 --> 01:27:06.230
like no, we're going no further.

01:27:06.230 --> 01:27:07.530
That's just not enough.

01:27:07.530 --> 01:27:09.610
We're not going to listen.

01:27:09.610 --> 01:27:12.570
Then perhaps, the opponent should
just go ahead and come forward

01:27:12.570 --> 01:27:15.910
with whatever reasons they
have, like the full bore,

01:27:15.910 --> 01:27:18.320
because otherwise, how do we
know what those reasons are

01:27:18.320 --> 01:27:21.050
and how do the proponents
respond, right?

01:27:21.050 --> 01:27:25.340
So, if there is information
that the opponents have,

01:27:25.340 --> 01:27:28.550
maybe they should go ahead and
disclose it or else, again,

01:27:28.550 --> 01:27:31.810 position:56%
maybe we can all agree that
sometimes that one page will just be

01:27:31.810 --> 01:27:35.880
on its face lame and
you can reject it.

01:27:35.880 --> 01:27:38.020
And then, maybe the one-page
thing is a good idea,

01:27:38.020 --> 01:27:41.610
as long as everybody's OK with
being killed at that stage

01:27:41.610 --> 01:27:44.910
and not going forward
to the full thing.

01:27:46.250 --> 01:27:48.020
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Thank you.

01:27:48.020 --> 01:27:50.140
Well, we are two minutes early.

01:27:50.140 --> 01:27:52.140
So, I'll consider that
a minor victory.

